[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Input and output operations on a computer can be extremely slow compared to the processing of data.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] An I/O device can incorporate mechanical devices that must physically move, such as a hard drive seeking a track to read or write; this is often orders of magnitude slower than the switching of electric current.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] For example, during a disk operation that takes ten milliseconds to perform, a processor that is clocked at one gigahertz could have performed ten million instruction-processing cycles.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] A simple approach to I/O would be to start the access and then wait for it to complete.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] But such an approach, called **synchronous I/O** or **blocking I/O**, would block the progress of a program while the communication is in progress, leaving system resources idle.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] When a program makes many I/O operations (such as a program mainly or largely dependent on user input), this means that the processor can spend almost all of its time idle waiting for I/O operations to complete.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Alternatively, it is possible to start the communication and then perform processing that does not require that the I/O be completed.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This approach is called asynchronous input/output.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Many operating system functions exist to implement asynchronous I/O at many levels.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] In fact, one of the main functions of all but the most rudimentary of operating systems is to perform at least some form of basic asynchronous I/O, though this may not be particularly apparent to the user or the programmer.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] In the simplest software solution, the hardware device status is polled at intervals to detect whether the device is ready for its next operation.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] (For example, the CP/M operating system was built this way.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Multitasking operating systems can exploit the functionality provided by hardware interrupts, whilst hiding the complexity of interrupt handling from the user.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Spooling was one of the first forms of multitasking designed to exploit asynchronous I/O.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Finally, multithreading and explicit asynchronous I/O APIs within user processes can exploit asynchronous I/O further, at the cost of extra software complexity.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Asynchronous I/O is used to improve energy efficiency, and in some cases throughput.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] However, it can have negative effects on latency and throughput in some cases.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] All forms of asynchronous I/O open applications up to potential resource conflicts and associated failure.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Careful programming (often using mutual exclusion, semaphores, etc.) is required to prevent this.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] When exposing asynchronous I/O to applications there are a few broad classes of implementation.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The form of the API provided to the application does not necessarily correspond with the mechanism actually provided by the operating system; emulations are possible.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Furthermore, more than one method may be used by a single application, depending on its needs and the desires of its programmer(s).
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Many operating systems provide more than one of these mechanisms, it is possible that some may provide all of them.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] In a multitasking operating system, processing can be distributed across different processes, which run independently, have their own memory, and process their own I/O flows; these flows are typically connected in pipelines.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Processes are fairly expensive to create and maintain, so this solution only works well if the set of processes is small and relatively stable.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] It also assumes that the individual processes can operate independently, apart from processing each other's I/O; if they need to communicate in other ways, coordinating them can become difficult.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] An extension of this approach is dataflow programming, which allows more complicated networks than just the chains that pipes support.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Polling provides non-blocking synchronous API which may be used to implement some asynchronous API.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Available in traditional Unix and Windows.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Its major problem is that it can waste CPU time polling repeatedly when there is nothing else for the issuing process to do, reducing the time available for other processes.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Also, because a polling application is essentially single-threaded it may be unable to fully exploit I/O parallelism that the hardware is capable of.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Available in BSD Unix, and almost anything else with a TCP/IP protocol stack that either utilizes or is modeled after the BSD implementation.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] A variation on the theme of polling, a select loop uses the `select` system call to sleep until a condition occurs on a file descriptor (e.g., when data is available for reading), a timeout occurs, or a signal is received (e.g., when a child process dies).
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] By examining the return parameters of the `select` call, the loop finds out which file descriptor has changed and executes the appropriate code.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Often, for ease of use, the select loop is implemented as an event loop, perhaps using callback functions; the situation lends itself particularly well to event-driven programming.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] While this method is reliable and relatively efficient, it depends heavily on the Unix paradigm that "everything is a file"; any blocking I/O that does not involve a file descriptor will block the process.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The select loop also relies on being able to involve all I/O in the central `select` call; libraries that conduct their own I/O are particularly problematic in this respect.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Some Unixes provide system-specific calls with better scaling; for example, `epoll` in Linux (that fills the return selection array with only those event sources on which an event has occurred), `kqueue` in FreeBSD, and event ports (and `/dev/poll`) in Solaris.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] SVR3 Unix provided the `poll` system call.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Arguably better-named than `select`, for the purposes of this discussion it is essentially the same thing.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] SVR4 Unixes (and thus POSIX) offer both calls.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] I/O is issued asynchronously, and when it is completed a signal (interrupt) is generated.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] As in low-level kernel programming, the facilities available for safe use within the signal handler are limited, and the main flow of the process could have been interrupted at nearly any point, resulting in inconsistent data structures as seen by the signal handler.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The signal handler is usually not able to issue further asynchronous I/O by itself.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The *signal* approach, though relatively simple to implement within the OS, brings to the application program the unwelcome baggage associated with writing an operating system's kernel interrupt system.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Its worst characteristic is that *every* blocking (synchronous) system call is potentially interruptible; the programmer must usually incorporate retry code at each call.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Available in the classic Mac OS, VMS and Windows.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Bears many of the characteristics of the *signal* method as it is fundamentally the same thing, though rarely recognized as such.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The difference is that each I/O request usually can have its own completion function, whereas the *signal* system has a single callback.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] On the other hand, a potential problem of using callbacks is that stack depth can grow unmanageably, as an extremely common thing to do when one I/O is finished is to schedule another.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] If this should be satisfied immediately, the first callback is not 'unwound' off the stack before the next one is invoked.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Systems to prevent this (like 'mid-ground' scheduling of new work) add complexity and reduce performance.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] In practice, however, this is generally not a problem because the new I/O will itself usually return as soon as the new I/O is started allowing the stack to be 'unwound'.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The problem can also be prevented by avoiding any further callbacks, by means of a queue, until the first callback returns.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Light-weight processes (LWPs) or threads are available in most modern operating systems.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Like the *process* method, but with lower overhead and without the data isolation that hampers coordination of the flows.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Each LWP or thread itself uses traditional blocking synchronous I/O, which simplifies programming logic; this is a common paradigm used in many programming languages including Java and Rust.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Multithreading needs to use kernel-provided synchronization mechanisms and thread-safe libraries.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This method is most suitable for extremely large-scale applications like web servers due to the large numbers of threads needed.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This approach is also used in the Erlang programming language runtime system.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The Erlang virtual machine uses asynchronous I/O using a small pool of only a few threads or sometimes just one process, to handle I/O from up to millions of Erlang processes.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] I/O handling in each process is written mostly using blocking synchronous I/O.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This way high performance of asynchronous I/O is merged with simplicity of normal I/O (cf. the Actor model).
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Many I/O problems in Erlang are mapped to message passing, which can be easily processed using built-in selective receive.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Fibers / Coroutines can be viewed as a similarly lightweight approach to do asynchronous I/O outside of the Erlang runtime system, although they do not provide exactly the same guarantees as Erlang processes.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Available in Microsoft Windows, Solaris, AmigaOS, DNIX and Linux (using io_uring, available on 5.1 and above).
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] I/O requests are issued asynchronously, but notifications of completion are provided via a synchronizing queue mechanism in the order they are completed.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Usually associated with a state-machine structuring of the main process (event-driven programming), which can bear little resemblance to a process that does not use asynchronous I/O or that uses one of the other forms, hampering code reuse.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Does not require additional special synchronization mechanisms or thread-safe libraries, nor are the textual (code) and time (event) flows separated.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Available in VMS and AmigaOS (often used in conjunction with a completion port).
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Bears many of the characteristics of the *completion queue* method, as it is essentially a completion queue of depth one.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] To simulate the effect of queue 'depth', an additional event flag is required for each potential unprocessed (but completed) event, or event information can be lost.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Waiting for the next available event in such a clump requires synchronizing mechanisms that may not scale well to larger numbers of potentially parallel events.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Available in mainframes by IBM, Groupe Bull, and Unisys.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Channel I/O is designed to maximize CPU utilization and throughput by offloading most I/O onto a coprocessor.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The coprocessor has onboard DMA, handles device interrupts, is controlled by the main CPU, and only interrupts the main CPU when it's truly necessary.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This architecture also supports so-called channel programs that run on the channel processor to do heavy lifting for I/O activities and protocols.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Available in Windows Server 2012 and Windows 8.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Optimized for applications that process large numbers of small messages to achieve higher I/O operations per second with reduced jitter and latency.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The vast majority of general-purpose computing hardware relies entirely upon two methods of implementing asynchronous I/O: polling and interrupts.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Usually both methods are used together, the balance depends heavily upon the design of the hardware and its required performance characteristics.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Pure polling systems are entirely possible, small microcontrollers (such as systems using the PIC microcontroller) are often built this way.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] CP/M systems could also be built this way (though rarely were), with or without DMA.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Also, when the utmost performance is necessary for only a *few* tasks, at the expense of any other potential tasks, polling may also be appropriate as the overhead of taking interrupts may be unwelcome.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Most general-purpose computing systems rely heavily upon interrupts.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] A pure interrupt system may be possible, though usually some component of polling is also required, as it is very common for multiple potential sources of interrupts to share a common interrupt signal line, in which case polling is used within the device driver to resolve the actual source.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] (This resolution time also contributes to an interrupt system's performance penalty.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Over the years a great deal of work has been done to try to minimize the overhead associated with servicing an interrupt.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Hybrid approaches are also possible, wherein an interrupt can trigger the beginning of some burst of asynchronous I/O, and polling is used within the burst itself.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This technique is common in high-speed device drivers, such as network or disk, where the time lost in returning to the pre-interrupt task is greater than the time until the next required servicing.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] (Common I/O hardware in use these days relies heavily upon DMA and large data buffers to make up for a relatively poorly-performing interrupt system.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] These characteristically use polling inside the driver loops, and can exhibit tremendous throughput.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] At one time this sort of hybrid approach was common in disk and network drivers where there was not DMA or significant buffering available.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] (In effect using the processor itself as a DMA engine.) The 6502 processor offered an unusual means to provide a three-element per-datum loop, as it had a hardware pin that, when asserted, would cause the processor's Overflow bit to be set directly.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Using only these two tools (polling, and interrupts), all the other forms of asynchronous I/O discussed above may be (and in fact, are) synthesized.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] In an environment such as a Java virtual machine (JVM), asynchronous I/O can be synthesized *even though* the environment the JVM is running in may not offer it at all.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This is due to the interpreted nature of the JVM.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The JVM may poll (or take an interrupt) periodically to institute an internal flow of control change, effecting the appearance of multiple simultaneous processes, at least some of which presumably exist in order to perform asynchronous I/O.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] That, in fact, is the problem with using polling in any form to synthesize a different form of asynchronous I/O.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Every CPU cycle that is a poll is wasted, and lost to overhead rather than accomplishing a desired task.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Every CPU cycle that is *not* a poll represents an increase in latency of reaction to pending I/O.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Striking an acceptable balance between these two opposing forces is difficult.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The trick to maximize efficiency is to minimize the amount of work that has to be done upon reception of an interrupt in order to awaken the appropriate application.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Secondarily (but perhaps no less important) is the method the application itself uses to determine what it needs to do.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Particularly problematic (for application efficiency) are the exposed polling methods, including the select/poll mechanisms.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Though the underlying I/O events they are interested in are in all likelihood interrupt-driven, the interaction *to* this mechanism is polled and can consume a large amount of time in the poll.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] This is particularly true of the potentially large-scale polling possible through select (and poll).
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] Interrupts map very well to Signals, Callback functions, Completion Queues, and Event flags, such systems can be very efficient.
[src:sqlx-rust/asynchronous-i-o] The following examples show three approaches to reading I/O.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] In software engineering, a **connection pool** is a cache of reusable database connections managed by the client or middleware.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] It reduces the overhead of opening and closing connections, improving performance and scalability in database applications.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] SQL databases typically use stateful, binary protocols that maintain session-specific information, such as transaction states and prepared statements, necessitating optimized connection pooling to minimize the overhead of repeatedly establishing connections.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Conversely, many mainstream NoSQL databases, like Azure Cosmos DB and Amazon DynamoDB, utilize stateless, HTTP-based protocols that handle each request independently.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] This architecture often reduces the need for traditional connection pooling, though reusing established connections can still offer performance benefits in high-throughput scenarios by avoiding the overhead of connection creation.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] In database environments, connection limits are typically determined by service tiers or resource configurations.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Azure SQL Database defines connection limits based on the selected tier, while Azure SQL Managed Instance enforces limits based on allocated resources, such as CPU, memory, or vCores.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] When connection pool configurations exceed these limits, issues such as rejected connections, throttling, or degraded performance can occur.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Depending on how database limits are applied, overprovisioned connection pools can create significant resource contention as the server struggles to manage excessive simultaneous connections.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Idle connections may encounter issues due to network conditions, such as NAT timeouts or dropped connections, or database state changes, such as session invalidation or transaction timeouts, potentially triggering reconnection processes that introduce additional overhead and performance penalties.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Over-provisioned pools can overwhelm server resources, causing increased latency and degraded system performance.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Token-based authentication mechanisms, such as Azure AD authentication, may affect connection pooling due to token expiration.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Expired tokens can invalidate connections within the pool, interrupting reuse.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] This behavior is observed in both cloud-based and on-premises database systems that implement modern authentication protocols.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] The efficiency of connection pooling can be influenced by network latency and endpoint configurations.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Public endpoints, commonly used in cloud-hosted databases, often introduce higher latency compared to private or direct connections.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] In environments with dynamic IP addressing, such as those involving cloud-native applications, disruptions in connection reuse may occur if firewall rules are not synchronized with changing IP addresses.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Databases that enforce TLS encryption, including those deployed in cloud and on-premises environments, require alignment between encryption settings and connection configurations.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] For example, the absence of encryption parameters in connection strings can lead to connection failures, rendering the pool ineffective.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Private endpoints and custom DNS configurations can create challenges for connection pooling.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Inconsistent or misconfigured DNS settings may delay or block connection establishment, affecting the performance and efficiency of connection reuse.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] This is particularly notable in environments with hybrid or private cloud setups.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] In modern cloud architectures like AWS, effective connection pooling management is critical for optimizing performance, scalability, and resource utilization.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Improper handling of connections can lead to bottlenecks and operational inefficiencies.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Containerized Environments: Amazon Elastic Container Service (ECS) containers maintain open database connections for their lifecycle.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Without connection pooling mechanisms (e.g., HikariCP, pgbouncer), idle or excessive connections can strain database resources.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Virtual Machine-Based Environments: AWS EC2 instances scale connection demand with the number of instances.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Manual or automated tuning of connection pool parameters is essential to prevent exceeding database limits.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] This ecosystem of tools and services empowers architects to design highly scalable and efficient applications while minimizing connection management overhead.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Azure SQL Database, Azure SQL Managed Instance, and SQL Server on virtual machines rely on client-side connection pooling implemented by libraries such as ADO.NET and JDBC.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] The database engine does not manage pooling, as it is entirely handled at the client level.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] Environmental factors, including service-tier limits in Azure SQL Database and resource constraints in Managed Instance, may indirectly affect pooling performance.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] In Azure Cosmos DB, connection pooling is managed at the SDK level rather than by the database service itself.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] SDKs such as those for .NET, Java, and Python implement connection pooling to reuse HTTP connections to the database endpoint, optimizing resource usage and performance.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] This functionality applies to all Cosmos DB account types, including provisioned throughput and serverless models.
[src:sqlx-rust/connection-pool] The stateless, HTTP-based architecture of Cosmos DB facilitates scalable and concurrent operations without the limitations typically associated with traditional connection pooling mechanisms.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] A **database connection** is a facility in computer science that allows client software to talk to database server software, whether on the same machine or not.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] A **connection** is required to send commands and receive answers, usually in the form of a result set.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] Connections are a key concept in data-centric programming.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] Since some DBMS engines require considerable time to connect, connection pooling was invented to improve performance.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] No command can be performed against a database without an "open and available" connection to it.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] Connections are built by supplying an underlying driver or provider with a connection string, which is a way of addressing a specific database or server and instance as well as user authentication credentials (for example, ***Server=**sql_box;**Database=**Common;**User ID=**uid;**Pwd=**password;*).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] Once a connection has been built it can be opened and closed at will, and properties (such as the command time-out length, or transaction, if one exists) can be set.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] The Connection String is composed of a set of key/value pairs as dictated by the data access interface and data provider being used.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] Many databases (such as PostgreSQL) only allow one operation to be performed at a time on each connection.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] If a request for data (a SQL Select statement) is sent to the database and a result set is returned, the connection is open but not available for other operations until the client finishes consuming the result set.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] Other databases, like SQL Server 2005 (and later), do not impose this limitation.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] However, databases that provide multiple operations per connection usually incur far more overhead than those that permit only a single operation task at a time.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] Database connections are finite and expensive and can take a disproportionately long time to create relative to the operations performed on them.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] It is inefficient for an application to create, use, and close a database connection whenever it needs to update a database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] Connection pooling is a technique designed to alleviate this problem.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] A pool of database connections can be created and then shared among the applications that need to access the database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] The connection object obtained from the connection pool is often a wrapper around the actual database connection.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] The wrapper understands its relationship with the pool, and hides the details of the pool from the application.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] For example, the wrapper object can implement a "close" method that can be called just like the "close" method on the database connection.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] Unlike the method on the database connection, the method on the wrapper may not actually close the database connection, but instead return it to the pool.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] The application need not be aware of the connection pooling when it calls the methods on the wrapper object.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] This approach encourages the practice of opening a connection in an application only when needed, and closing it as soon as the work is done, rather than holding a connection open for the entire life of the application.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] In this manner, a relatively small number of connections can service a large number of requests.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] In a client/server architecture, on the other hand, a persistent connection is typically used so that server state can be managed.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] This "state" includes server-side cursors, temporary products, connection-specific functional settings, and so on.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] An application failure occurs when the connection pool overflows.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] This can occur if all of the connections in the pool are in use when an application requests a connection.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-connection] For example, the application may use a connection for too long when too many clients attempt to access the web site or one or more operations are blocked or simply inefficient.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In computing, a **database** is an organized collection of data or a type of data store based on the use of a **database management system** (**DBMS**), the software that interacts with end users, applications, and the database itself to capture and analyze the data.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The DBMS additionally encompasses the core facilities provided to administer the database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The sum total of the database, the DBMS and the associated applications can be referred to as a **database system**.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Often the term "database" is also used loosely to refer to any of the DBMS, the database system or an application associated with the database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Professional book indexers used index cards in the creation of book indexes until they were replaced by indexing software in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Small databases can be stored on a file system, while large databases are hosted on computer clusters or cloud storage.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The design of databases spans formal techniques and practical considerations, including data modeling, efficient data representation and storage, query languages, security and privacy of sensitive data, and distributed computing issues, including supporting concurrent access and fault tolerance.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Computer scientists may classify database management systems according to the database models that they support.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Relational databases became dominant in the 1980s.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] These model data as rows and columns in a series of tables, and the vast majority use SQL for writing and querying data.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In the 2000s, non-relational databases became popular, collectively referred to as NoSQL, because they use different query languages.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The DBMS provides various functions that allow entry, storage and retrieval of large quantities of information and provides ways to manage how that information is organized.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Because of the close relationship between them, the term "database" is often used casually to refer to both a database and the DBMS used to manipulate it.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Outside the world of professional information technology, the term *database* is often used to refer to any collection of related data (such as a spreadsheet or a card index) as size and usage requirements typically necessitate use of a database management system.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Both a database and its DBMS conform to the principles of a particular database model.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] "Database system" refers collectively to the database model, database management system, and database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Physically, database servers are dedicated computers that hold the actual databases and run only the DBMS and related software.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Database servers are usually multiprocessor computers, with generous memory and RAID disk arrays used for stable storage.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Hardware database accelerators, connected to one or more servers via a high-speed channel, are also used in large-volume transaction processing environments.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] DBMSs are found at the heart of most database applications.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] DBMSs may be built around a custom multitasking kernel with built-in networking support, but modern DBMSs typically rely on a standard operating system to provide these functions.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Since DBMSs comprise a significant market, computer and storage vendors often take into account DBMS requirements in their own development plans.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The sizes, capabilities, and performance of databases and their respective DBMSs have grown in orders of magnitude.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] These performance increases were enabled by the technology progress in the areas of processors, computer memory, computer storage, and computer networks.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The concept of a database was made possible by the emergence of direct access storage media such as magnetic disks, which became widely available in the mid-1960s; earlier systems relied on sequential storage of data on magnetic tape.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The subsequent development of database technology can be divided into three eras based on data model or structure: navigational, SQL/relational, and post-relational.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The two main early navigational data models were the hierarchical model and the CODASYL model (network model).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] These were characterized by the use of pointers (often physical disk addresses) to follow relationships from one record to another.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The relational model, first proposed in 1970 by Edgar F.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Codd, departed from this tradition by insisting that applications should search for data by content, rather than by following links.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The relational model employs sets of ledger-style tables, each used for a different type of entity.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Only in the mid-1980s did computing hardware become powerful enough to allow the wide deployment of relational systems (DBMSs plus applications).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] By the early 1990s, however, relational systems dominated in all large-scale data processing applications, and as of 2018 they remain dominant: IBM Db2, Oracle, MySQL, and Microsoft SQL Server are the most searched DBMS.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The dominant database language, standardized SQL for the relational model, has influenced database languages for other data models.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Object databases were developed in the 1980s to overcome the inconvenience of object–relational impedance mismatch, which led to the coining of the term "post-relational" and also the development of hybrid object–relational databases.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The next generation of post-relational databases in the late 2000s became known as NoSQL databases, introducing fast key–value stores and document-oriented databases.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] A competing "next generation" known as NewSQL databases attempted new implementations that retained the relational/SQL model while aiming to match the high performance of NoSQL compared to commercially available relational DBMSs.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The introduction of the term *database* coincided with the availability of direct-access storage (disks and drums) from the mid-1960s onwards.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The term represented a contrast with the tape-based systems of the past, allowing shared interactive use rather than daily batch processing.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The Oxford English Dictionary cites a 1962 report by the System Development Corporation of California as the first to use the term "data-base" in a specific technical sense.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] As computers grew in speed and capability, a number of general-purpose database systems emerged; by the mid-1960s a number of such systems had come into commercial use.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Interest in a standard began to grow, and Charles Bachman, author of one such product, the Integrated Data Store (IDS), founded the Database Task Group within CODASYL, the group responsible for the creation and standardization of COBOL.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In 1971, the Database Task Group delivered their standard, which generally became known as the *CODASYL approach*, and soon a number of commercial products based on this approach entered the market.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The CODASYL approach offered applications the ability to navigate around a linked data set which was formed into a large network.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Later systems added B-trees to provide alternate access paths.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Many CODASYL databases also added a declarative query language for end users (as distinct from the navigational API).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] However, CODASYL databases were complex and required significant training and effort to produce useful applications.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] IBM also had its own DBMS in 1966, known as Information Management System (IMS).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] IMS was a development of software written for the Apollo program on the System/360.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] IMS was generally similar in concept to CODASYL, but used a strict hierarchy for its model of data navigation instead of CODASYL's network model.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Both concepts later became known as navigational databases due to the way data was accessed: the term was popularized by Bachman's 1973 Turing Award presentation *The Programmer as Navigator*.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] IMS is classified by IBM as a hierarchical database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] IDMS and Cincom Systems' TOTAL databases are classified as network databases.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Codd worked at IBM in San Jose, California, in an office primarily involved in the development of hard disk systems.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] He was unhappy with the navigational model of the CODASYL approach, notably the lack of a "search" facility.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In 1970, he wrote a number of papers that outlined a new approach to database construction that eventually culminated in the groundbreaking *A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks*.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The paper described a new system for storing and working with large databases.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Instead of records being stored in some sort of linked list of free-form records as in CODASYL, Codd's idea was to organize the data as a number of "tables", each table being used for a different type of entity.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Each table would contain a fixed number of columns containing the attributes of the entity.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Splitting the data into a set of normalized tables (or *relations*) aimed to ensure that each "fact" was only stored once, thus simplifying update operations.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Virtual tables called *views* could present the data in different ways for different users, but views could not be directly updated.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Codd used mathematical terms to define the model: relations, tuples, and domains rather than tables, rows, and columns.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The terminology that is now familiar came from early implementations.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Codd would later criticize the tendency for practical implementations to depart from the mathematical foundations on which the model was based.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The use of primary keys (user-oriented identifiers) to represent cross-table relationships, rather than disk addresses, had two primary motivations.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] From an engineering perspective, it enabled tables to be relocated and resized without expensive database reorganization.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] There is no loss of expressiveness compared with the hierarchic or network models, though the connections between tables are no longer so explicit.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In the hierarchic and network models, records were allowed to have a complex internal structure.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] For example, the salary history of an employee might be represented as a "repeating group" within the employee record.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In the relational model, the process of normalization led to such internal structures being replaced by data held in multiple tables, connected only by logical keys.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] For instance, a common use of a database system is to track information about users, their name, login information, various addresses and phone numbers.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In the navigational approach, all of this data would be placed in a single variable-length record.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In the relational approach, the data would be *normalized* into a user table, an address table and a phone number table (for instance).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Records would be created in these optional tables only if the address or phone numbers were actually provided.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] As well as identifying rows/records using logical identifiers rather than disk addresses, Codd changed the way in which applications assembled data from multiple records.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Rather than requiring applications to gather data one record at a time by navigating the links, they would use a declarative query language that expressed what data was required, rather than the access path by which it should be found.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Finding an efficient access path to the data became the responsibility of the database management system, rather than the application programmer.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] This process, called query optimization, depended on the fact that queries were expressed in terms of mathematical logic.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Beginning in 1973, INGRES delivered its first test products which were generally ready for widespread use in 1979.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] INGRES was similar to System R in a number of ways, including the use of a "language" for data access, known as QUEL.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Over time, INGRES moved to the emerging SQL standard.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] IBM itself did one test implementation of the relational model, PRTV, and a production one, Business System 12, both now discontinued.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Honeywell wrote MRDS for Multics, and now there are two new implementations: Alphora Dataphor and Rel.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Most other DBMS implementations usually called *relational* are actually SQL DBMSs.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In 1970, the University of Michigan began development of the MICRO Information Management System based on D.L.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The university in 1974 hosted a debate between Codd and Bachman which Bruce Lindsay of IBM later described as "throwing lightning bolts at each other!".
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] MICRO was used to manage very large data sets by the US Department of Labor, the U.S.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Environmental Protection Agency, and researchers from the University of Alberta, the University of Michigan, and Wayne State University.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] It ran on IBM mainframe computers using the Michigan Terminal System.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The system remained in production until 1998.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In the 1970s and 1980s, attempts were made to build database systems with integrated hardware and software.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The underlying philosophy was that such integration would provide higher performance at a lower cost.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Examples were IBM System/38, the early offering of Teradata, and the Britton Lee, Inc. database machine.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Another approach to hardware support for database management was ICL's CAFS accelerator, a hardware disk controller with programmable search capabilities.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In the long term, these efforts were generally unsuccessful because specialized database machines could not keep pace with the rapid development and progress of general-purpose computers.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Thus most database systems nowadays are software systems running on general-purpose hardware, using general-purpose computer data storage.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] However, this idea is still pursued in certain applications by some companies like Netezza and Oracle (Exadata).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] IBM formed a team led by Codd that started working on a prototype system, *System R* despite opposition from others at the company.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The first version was ready in 1974/5, and work then started on multi-table systems in which the data could be split so that all of the data for a record (some of which is optional) did not have to be stored in a single large "chunk".
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Subsequent multi-user versions were tested by customers in 1978 and 1979, by which time a standardized query language – SQL – had been added.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Codd's ideas were establishing themselves as both workable and superior to CODASYL, pushing IBM to develop a true production version of System R, known as *SQL/DS*, and, later, *Database 2* (IBM Db2).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Larry Ellison's Oracle Database (or more simply, Oracle) started from a different chain, based on IBM's papers on System R.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Though Oracle V1 implementations were completed in 1978, it was not until Oracle Version 2 when Ellison beat IBM to market in 1979.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Stonebraker went on to apply the lessons from INGRES to develop a new database, Postgres, which is now known as PostgreSQL.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] PostgreSQL is often used for global mission-critical applications (the .org and .info domain name registries use it as their primary data store, as do many large companies and financial institutions).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In Sweden, Codd's paper was also read and Mimer SQL was developed in the mid-1970s at Uppsala University.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In 1984, this project was consolidated into an independent enterprise.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Another data model, the entity–relationship model, emerged in 1976 and gained popularity for database design as it emphasized a more familiar description than the earlier relational model.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Later on, entity–relationship constructs were retrofitted as a data modeling construct for the relational model, and the difference between the two has become irrelevant.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Besides IBM and various software companies such as Sybase and Informix Corporation, most large computer hardware vendors by the 1980s had their own database systems such as DEC's VAX Rdb/VMS.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The decade ushered in the age of desktop computing.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The new computers empowered their users with spreadsheets like Lotus 1-2-3 and database software like dBASE.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The dBASE product was lightweight and easy for any computer user to understand out of the box.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Wayne Ratliff, the creator of dBASE, stated: "dBASE was different from programs like BASIC, C, FORTRAN, and COBOL in that a lot of the dirty work had already been done.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] By the start of the decade databases had become a billion-dollar industry in about ten years.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The 1990s, along with a rise in object-oriented programming, saw a growth in how data in various databases were handled.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Programmers and designers began to treat the data in their databases as objects.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] That is to say that if a person's data were in a database, that person's attributes, such as their address, phone number, and age, were now considered to belong to that person instead of being extraneous data.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] This allows for relations between data to be related to objects and their attributes and not to individual fields.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The term "object–relational impedance mismatch" described the inconvenience of translating between programmed objects and database tables.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Object databases and object–relational databases attempt to solve this problem by providing an object-oriented language (sometimes as extensions to SQL) that programmers can use as alternative to purely relational SQL.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] On the programming side, libraries known as object–relational mappings (ORMs) attempt to solve the same problem.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Database sales grew rapidly during the dotcom bubble and, after its end, the rise of ecommerce.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The popularity of open source databases such as MySQL has grown since 2000, to the extent that Ken Jacobs of Oracle said in 2005 that perhaps "these guys are doing to us what we did to IBM".
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] XML databases are a type of structured document-oriented database that allows querying based on XML document attributes.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] XML databases are mostly used in applications where the data is conveniently viewed as a collection of documents, with a structure that can vary from the very flexible to the highly rigid: examples include scientific articles, patents, tax filings, and personnel records.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] NoSQL databases are often very fast, do not require fixed table schemas, avoid join operations by storing denormalized data, and are designed to scale horizontally.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Some NoSQL databases, including graph databases such as Neo4j, represent data as nodes and edges to model relationships between entities.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In recent years, there has been a strong demand for massively distributed databases with high partition tolerance, but according to the CAP theorem, it is impossible for a distributed system to simultaneously provide consistency, availability, and partition tolerance guarantees.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] A distributed system can satisfy any two of these guarantees at the same time, but not all three.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] For that reason, many NoSQL databases are using what is called eventual consistency to provide both availability and partition tolerance guarantees with a reduced level of data consistency.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] NewSQL is a class of modern relational databases that aims to provide the same scalable performance of NoSQL systems for online transaction processing (read-write) workloads while still using SQL and maintaining the ACID guarantees of a traditional database system.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Databases are used to support internal operations of organizations and to underpin online interactions with customers and suppliers (see Enterprise software).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Databases are used to hold administrative information and more specialized data, such as engineering data or economic models.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Examples include computerized library systems, flight reservation systems, computerized parts inventory systems, and many content management systems that store websites as collections of webpages in a database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] One way to classify databases involves the type of their contents, for example: bibliographic, document-text, statistical, or multimedia objects.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Another way is by their application area, for example: accounting, music compositions, movies, banking, manufacturing, or insurance.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] A third way is by some technical aspect, such as the database structure or interface type.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] This section lists a few of the adjectives used to characterize different kinds of databases.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database." Examples of DBMS's include MySQL, MariaDB, PostgreSQL, Microsoft SQL Server, Oracle Database, and Microsoft Access.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The DBMS acronym is sometimes extended to indicate the underlying database model, with RDBMS for the relational, OODBMS for the object (oriented) and ORDBMS for the object–relational model.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Other extensions can indicate some other characteristics, such as DDBMS for a distributed database management systems.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The functionality provided by a DBMS can vary enormously.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The core functionality is the storage, retrieval and update of data.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] It is also generally to be expected the DBMS will provide a set of utilities for such purposes as may be necessary to administer the database effectively, including import, export, monitoring, defragmentation and analysis utilities.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The core part of the DBMS interacting between the database and the application interface sometimes referred to as the database engine.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Often DBMSs will have configuration parameters that can be statically and dynamically tuned, for example the maximum amount of main memory on a server the database can use.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The trend is to minimize the amount of manual configuration, and for cases such as embedded databases the need to target zero-administration is paramount.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The large major enterprise DBMSs have tended to increase in size and functionality and have involved up to thousands of human years of development effort throughout their lifetime.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Early multi-user DBMS typically only allowed for the application to reside on the same computer with access via terminals or terminal emulation software.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The client–server architecture was a development where the application resided on a client desktop and the database on a server allowing the processing to be distributed.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] This evolved into a multitier architecture incorporating application servers and web servers with the end user interface via a web browser with the database only directly connected to the adjacent tier.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] A general-purpose DBMS will provide public application programming interfaces (API) and optionally a processor for database languages such as SQL to allow applications to be written to interact with and manipulate the database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] A special purpose DBMS may use a private API and be specifically customized and linked to a single application.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] For example, an email system performs many of the functions of a general-purpose DBMS such as message insertion, message deletion, attachment handling, blocklist lookup, associating messages an email address and so forth however these functions are limited to what is required to handle email.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] External interaction with the database will be via an application program that interfaces with the DBMS.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] This can range from a database tool that allows users to execute SQL queries textually or graphically, to a website that happens to use a database to store and search information.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] A programmer will code interactions to the database (sometimes referred to as a datasource) via an application program interface (API) or via a database language.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The particular API or language chosen will need to be supported by DBMS, possibly indirectly via a preprocessor or a bridging API.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Some API's aim to be database independent, ODBC being a commonly known example.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Other common API's include JDBC and ADO.NET.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Database languages are specific to a particular data model.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Database storage is the container of the physical materialization of a database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] It comprises the *internal* (physical) *level* in the database architecture.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] It also contains all the information needed (e.g., metadata, "data about the data", and internal data structures) to reconstruct the *conceptual level* and *external level* from the internal level when needed.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Databases as digital objects contain three layers of information which must be stored: the data, the structure, and the semantics.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Proper storage of all three layers is needed for future preservation and longevity of the database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Putting data into permanent storage is generally the responsibility of the database engine a.k.a.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] A DBMS, while in operation, always has its database residing in several types of storage (e.g., memory and external storage).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The database data and the additional needed information, possibly in very large amounts, are coded into bits.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Some DBMSs support specifying which character encoding was used to store data, so multiple encodings can be used in the same database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Various low-level database storage structures are used by the storage engine to serialize the data model so it can be written to the medium of choice.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Techniques such as indexing may be used to improve performance.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Conventional storage is row-oriented, but there are also column-oriented and correlation databases.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Often storage redundancy is employed to increase performance.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] A common example is storing *materialized views*, which consist of frequently needed *external views* or query results.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Storing such views saves the expensive computing them each time they are needed.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The downsides of materialized views are the overhead incurred when updating them to keep them synchronized with their original updated database data, and the cost of storage redundancy.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Updates of a replicated object need to be synchronized across the object copies.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In many cases, the entire database is replicated.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Database security deals with all various aspects of protecting the database content, its owners, and its users.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] It ranges from protection from intentional unauthorized database uses to unintentional database accesses by unauthorized entities (e.g., a person or a computer program).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Database access control deals with controlling who (a person or a certain computer program) are allowed to access what information in the database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Database access controls are set by special authorized (by the database owner) personnel that uses dedicated protected security DBMS interfaces.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] This may be managed directly on an individual basis, or by the assignment of individuals and privileges to groups, or (in the most elaborate models) through the assignment of individuals and groups to roles which are then granted entitlements.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Data security prevents unauthorized users from viewing or updating the database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Using passwords, users are allowed access to the entire database or subsets of it called "subschemas".
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] For example, an employee database can contain all the data about an individual employee, but one group of users may be authorized to view only payroll data, while others are allowed access to only work history and medical data.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] If the DBMS provides a way to interactively enter and update the database, as well as interrogate it, this capability allows for managing personal databases.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Change and access logging records who accessed which attributes, what was changed, and when it was changed.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Logging services allow for a forensic database audit later by keeping a record of access occurrences and changes.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Sometimes application-level code is used to record changes rather than leaving this in the database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Monitoring can be set up to attempt to detect security breaches.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Therefore, organizations must take database security seriously because of the many benefits it provides.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Organizations will be safeguarded from security breaches and hacking activities like firewall intrusion, virus spread, and ransom ware.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] This helps in protecting the company's essential information, which cannot be shared with outsiders at any cause.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Database transactions can be used to introduce some level of fault tolerance and data integrity after recovery from a crash.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] A database transaction is a unit of work, typically encapsulating a number of operations over a database (e.g., reading a database object, writing, acquiring or releasing a lock, etc.), an abstraction supported in database and also other systems.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Each transaction has well defined boundaries in terms of which program/code executions are included in that transaction (determined by the transaction's programmer via special transaction commands).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The acronym ACID describes some ideal properties of a database transaction: atomicity, consistency, isolation, and durability.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] A database built with one DBMS is not portable to another DBMS (i.e., the other DBMS cannot run it).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] However, in some situations, it is desirable to migrate a database from one DBMS to another.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The reasons are primarily economical (different DBMSs may have different total costs of ownership or TCOs), functional, and operational (different DBMSs may have different capabilities).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The migration involves the database's transformation from one DBMS type to another.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] The transformation should maintain (if possible) the database related application (i.e., all related application programs) intact.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Thus, the database's conceptual and external architectural levels should be maintained in the transformation.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] It may be desired that also some aspects of the architecture internal level are maintained.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] A complex or large database migration may be a complicated and costly (one-time) project by itself, which should be factored into the decision to migrate.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] This is in spite of the fact that tools may exist to help migration between specific DBMSs.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Typically, a DBMS vendor provides tools to help import databases from other popular DBMSs.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] After designing a database for an application, the next stage is building the database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Typically, an appropriate general-purpose DBMS can be selected to be used for this purpose.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] A DBMS provides the needed user interfaces to be used by database administrators to define the needed application's data structures within the DBMS's respective data model.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Other user interfaces are used to select needed DBMS parameters (like security related, storage allocation parameters, etc.).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] In some cases, the database becomes operational while empty of application data, and data are accumulated during its operation.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] After the database is created, initialized and populated it needs to be maintained.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Various database parameters may need changing and the database may need to be tuned (tuning) for better performance; application's data structures may be changed or added, new related application programs may be written to add to the application's functionality, etc.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] Sometimes it is desired to bring a database back to a previous state (for many reasons, e.g., cases when the database is found corrupted due to a software error, or if it has been updated with erroneous data).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] To achieve this, a backup operation is done occasionally or continuously, where each desired database state (i.e., the values of its data and their embedding in database's data structures) is kept within dedicated backup files (many techniques exist to do this effectively).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p01] When it is decided by a database administrator to bring the database back to this state (e.g., by specifying this state by a desired point in time when the database was in this state), these files are used to restore that state.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] Static analysis techniques for software verification can be applied also in the scenario of query languages.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] In particular, the *Abstract interpretation framework has been extended to the field of query languages for relational databases as a way to support sound approximation techniques.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] The semantics of query languages can be tuned according to suitable abstractions of the concrete domain of data.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] The abstraction of relational database systems has many interesting applications, in particular, for security purposes, such as fine-grained access control, watermarking, etc.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] Increasingly, there are calls for a single system that incorporates all of these core functionalities into the same build, test, and deployment framework for database management and source control.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] Borrowing from other developments in the software industry, some market such offerings as "DevOps for database".
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] The first task of a database designer is to produce a conceptual data model that reflects the structure of the information to be held in the database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] A common approach to this is to develop an entity–relationship model, often with the aid of drawing tools.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] Another popular approach is the Unified Modeling Language.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] A successful data model will accurately reflect the possible state of the external world being modeled: for example, if people can have more than one phone number, it will allow this information to be captured.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] The answers to these questions establish definitions of the terminology used for entities (customers, products, flights, flight segments) and their relationships and attributes.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] Producing the conceptual data model sometimes involves input from business processes, or the analysis of workflow in the organization.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] This can help to establish what information is needed in the database, and what can be left out.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] For example, it can help when deciding whether the database needs to hold historic data as well as current data.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] Having produced a conceptual data model that users are happy with, the next stage is to translate this into a schema that implements the relevant data structures within the database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] This process is often called logical database design, and the output is a logical data model expressed in the form of a schema.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] Whereas the conceptual data model is (in theory at least) independent of the choice of database technology, the logical data model will be expressed in terms of a particular database model supported by the chosen DBMS.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] (The terms *data model* and *database model* are often used interchangeably, but in this article we use *data model* for the design of a specific database, and *database model* for the modeling notation used to express that design).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] The most popular database model for general-purpose databases is the relational model, or more precisely, the relational model as represented by the SQL language.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] The process of creating a logical database design using this model uses a methodical approach known as normalization.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] The goal of normalization is to ensure that each elementary "fact" is only recorded in one place, so that insertions, updates, and deletions automatically maintain consistency.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] The final stage of database design is to make the decisions that affect performance, scalability, recovery, security, and the like, which depend on the particular DBMS.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] This is often called *physical database design*, and the output is the physical data model.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] A key goal during this stage is data independence, meaning that the decisions made for performance optimization purposes should be invisible to end-users and applications.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] There are two types of data independence: Physical data independence and logical data independence.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] Physical design is driven mainly by performance requirements, and requires a good knowledge of the expected workload and access patterns, and a deep understanding of the features offered by the chosen DBMS.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] Another aspect of physical database design is security.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] It involves both defining access control to database objects as well as defining security levels and methods for the data itself.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] A database model is a type of data model that determines the logical structure of a database and fundamentally determines in which manner data can be stored, organized, and manipulated.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] The most popular example of a database model is the relational model (or the SQL approximation of relational), which uses a table-based format.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] An object–relational database combines the two related structures.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] While there is typically only one conceptual and internal view of the data, there can be any number of different external views.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] This allows users to see database information in a more business-related way rather than from a technical, processing viewpoint.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] For example, a financial department of a company needs the payment details of all employees as part of the company's expenses, but does not need details about employees that are in the interest of the human resources department.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] Thus different departments need different *views* of the company's database.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] The three-level database architecture relates to the concept of *data independence* which was one of the major initial driving forces of the relational model.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] The idea is that changes made at a certain level do not affect the view at a higher level.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] For example, changes in the internal level do not affect application programs written using conceptual level interfaces, which reduces the impact of making physical changes to improve performance.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] The conceptual view provides a level of indirection between internal and external.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] On the one hand it provides a common view of the database, independent of different external view structures, and on the other hand it abstracts away details of how the data are stored or managed (internal level).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] In principle every level, and even every external view, can be presented by a different data model.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] In practice usually a given DBMS uses the same data model for both the external and the conceptual levels (e.g., relational model).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] The internal level, which is hidden inside the DBMS and depends on its implementation, requires a different level of detail and uses its own types of data structure types.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] Database technology has been an active research topic since the 1960s, both in academia and in the research and development groups of companies (for example IBM Research).
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] Research activity includes theory and development of prototypes.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] Notable research topics have included models, the atomic transaction concept, related concurrency control techniques, query languages and query optimization methods, RAID, and more.
[src:sqlx-rust/database-p02] The database research area has several dedicated academic journals (for example, *ACM Transactions on Database Systems*-TODS, *Data and Knowledge Engineering*-DKE) and annual conferences (e.g., ACM SIGMOD, ACM PODS, VLDB, IEEE ICDE).
[src:sqlx-rust/latest-sqlx] The async SQL toolkit for Rust, built with ❤️ by the LaunchBadge team.
[src:sqlx-rust/latest-sqlx] See our README to get started or browse our example projects.
[src:sqlx-rust/latest-sqlx] SQLx supports both the Tokio and async-std runtimes.
[src:sqlx-rust/latest-sqlx] If more than one runtime feature is enabled, the Tokio runtime is used if a Tokio context exists on the current thread, i.e.
[src:sqlx-rust/latest-sqlx] `tokio::runtime::Handle::try_current()` returns `Ok`; `async-std` is used otherwise.
[src:sqlx-rust/latest-sqlx] Note that while SQLx no longer produces a compile error if zero or multiple runtime features are enabled, which is useful for libraries building on top of it, **the use of nearly any async function in the API will panic without at least one runtime feature enabled**.
[src:sqlx-rust/latest-sqlx] The chief exception is the SQLite driver, which is runtime-agnostic, including its integration with the query macros.
[src:sqlx-rust/latest-sqlx] However, `SqlitePool` *does* require runtime support for timeouts and spawning internal management tasks.
[src:sqlx-rust/latest-sqlx] If more than one TLS feature is enabled, the `tls-native-tls` feature takes precedent so that it is only necessary to enable it to see if it resolves the `HandshakeFailure` error without disabling `tls-rustls`.
[src:sqlx-rust/latest-sqlx] Consult the user manual for your database to find the TLS versions it supports.
[src:sqlx-rust/latest-sqlx] If your connection configuration requires a TLS upgrade but TLS support was not enabled, the connection attempt will return an error.
[src:sqlx-rust/latest-sqlx] Types for working with errors produced by SQLx.
[src:sqlx-rust/latest-sqlx] Provides the connection pool for asynchronous SQLx connections.
